B = 14 / 62 ≈ 0.2258 (Approximate proportion).

However, according to the original formula, B should represent the proportion of words longer than 6 letters. I calculated it as the proportion of words having 7 letters or more, as traditionally only the 7-letter words are counted for B.

So the computed value is transformed like this to reach from a percentage of longer words to how many letters in the text are found in words longer than six letters per hundred words:   
So from 0.2258 in decimal form of ratio - multiply by 100 to make percent and round this percent and multiply that by the total number of words and multiply that by the word length of 7 letters [the smallest bigger-than-6-letter-word - a realistic approximation of what the LIX inventor intended - and subtract 50 - because the letters for the six-letter smaller-than-or-equal-to-6-words count - will double count some because they are all found in one-and-the same word. finally divide this whole product by (62 * 100): 

Result yields .16 (with rounded percent 23 to yield 15).

 
